**Classification**

*   [Indo-European languages](/Indo-European_languages)
    *   [Germanic](/Germanic_languages)
        *   [West Germanic](/West_Germanic_languages)
            *   [Low Franconian](/Low_Franconian_languages)
                *   Dutch
                *   Afrikaans, [Dutch-based creole languages](/Dutch-based_creole_languages)

Dutch occupies its own distinct niche within the [West Germanic](/West_Germanic_languages) family, classified under the [Low Franconian](/Low_Franconian) languages. It shares this classification with Limburgish, or East Low Franconian. Its closest living relative is Afrikaans, a [mutually intelligible](/Mutual_intelligibility) daughter language. Other West Germanic languages related to Dutch include [German](/German_language), [English](/English_language), the less standardized [Low German](/Low_German), and [Yiddish](/Yiddish).

Dutch is notable for its unique blend of [Ingvaeonic characteristics](/Ingvaeonic_nasal_spirant_law) – features found consistently in English and Frisian, and diminishing in intensity from west to east across the [continental West Germanic](/Continental_West_Germanic) plane – and dominant Istvaeonic characteristics, some of which are also present in German. Unlike German, Dutch (with the exception of Limburgish) was largely unaffected by the [High German consonant shift](/High_German_consonant_shift) moving from south to north. It underwent its own distinct sound changes. Over time, this confluence of influences resulted in separate, yet related, standard languages, each with varying degrees of similarity and divergence.

