**Dialects**

Dutch [dialects](/Dialect) are, by definition, those varieties closely related to the Dutch language and spoken within the same geographical area as the standard language. Despite the pervasive influence of the standard language, many retain their distinctiveness, found in both the [Netherlands](/Netherlands) and the [Flemish regions](/Flemish_region) of [Belgium](/Belgium), including [Brussels](/Brussels). The boundaries of these dialect areas often align with historical medieval counties and duchies.

Within the Netherlands, a distinction is made between a "dialect" and a *streektaal* ("[regional language](/Regional_language)"). These terms are more political than strictly linguistic, as a regional language can encompass a diverse range of varieties. For instance, the [Gronings dialect](/Gronings_dialect) is considered a variety of the [Dutch Low Saxon](/Dutch_Low_Saxon) regional language, yet it differs significantly from other Dutch Low Saxon varieties. Conversely, some Dutch dialects are more distant from the standard Dutch language than certain regional language varieties. The Netherlands also distinguishes between a regional language and a separate language, as is the case with [West Frisian](/West_Frisian_language), which is spoken alongside Dutch in the province of [Friesland](/Friesland).

The use of dialects and regional languages has seen a marked decline, particularly in the Netherlands. Recent research by Geert Driessen indicates a significant drop in regular usage among both adults and youth. In 1995, 27 percent of Dutch adults regularly spoke a dialect or regional language; by 2011, this figure had fallen to just 11 percent. Among primary school children, the decline was even steeper: from 12 percent in 1995 to a mere four percent in 2011. Among the officially recognized regional languages, [Limburgish](/Limburgish) fares best, spoken by 54 percent of adults and 31 percent of children in 2011, while Dutch Low Saxon is spoken by only 15 percent of adults and 1 percent of children. [West Frisian](/West_Frisian_language) in Friesland occupies a middle ground, with 44 percent of adults and 22 percent of children using it. Dialects are most prevalent in rural areas, but many cities boast their own distinct urban dialects. The dialect of [Ghent](/Ghent), for example, exhibits striking variations in its "g," "e," and "r" sounds compared to surrounding villages. The [Brussels](/Brussels) dialect is a blend of Brabantian with influences from [Walloon](/Walloon_language) and [French](/French_language).

Historically, some dialects extended beyond current national borders. However, the pervasive influence of the standard language has largely eroded these [dialect continuums](/Dialect_continuum). Examples include the [Gronings dialect](/Gronings_dialect) in [Groningen](/Groningen_(province)), which shares similarities with related varieties in adjacent [East Frisia](/East_Frisia) in Germany. [Kleverlandish](/Kleverlandish) is spoken in southern [Gelderland](/Gelderland), the northern tip of [Limburg](/Limburg_(Netherlands)), and northeast [North Brabant](/North_Brabant) in the Netherlands, as well as in adjacent parts of [North Rhine-Westphalia](/North_Rhine-Westphalia) in Germany. [Limburgish](/Limburgish_language) is found in [Limburg (Belgium)](/Limburg_(Belgium)), [Netherlands Limburg](/Limburg_(Netherlands)), and extends into Germany. [West Flemish](/West_Flemish) is spoken in [West Flanders](/West_Flanders), the western part of [Zeelandic Flanders](/Zeelandic_Flanders), and historically in [French Flanders](/French_Flanders), where it has largely succumbed to French.

**Dialect Groups**

The [West Flemish](/West_Flemish) dialect group, spoken in [West Flanders](/West_Flanders) and [Zeeland](/Zeeland), is so distinct that it could arguably be considered a separate language variant. However, political sensitivities in Belgium prevent such a classification. A peculiar feature of this dialect is the shift of the [voiced velar fricative](/Voiced_velar_fricative) (the Dutch "g") to a [voiced glottal fricative](/Voiced_glottal_fricative) (the Dutch "h"), while the letter "h" becomes mute, akin to French. Consequently, West Flemish speakers often struggle to pronounce the standard Dutch "g," rendering it as an "h," thus blurring the distinction between words like "held" (hero) and "geld" (money). Some, aware of this, overcompensate, turning the "h" into a velar fricative, again erasing the difference. The West Flemish dialect historically spoken in adjacent parts of France is known as [French Flemish](/French_Flemish) and is recognized as a French [minority language](/Minority_language). However, only a small, aging segment of the French-Flemish population still speaks and understands it.

[Hollandic](/Hollandic_dialect) is spoken in [Holland](/Holland) and [Utrecht](/Utrecht). The original forms, heavily influenced by a West Frisian [substratum](/Stratum_(linguistics)) and later by [Brabantian dialects](/Brabantian_dialect), are now uncommon. The urban dialects of the [Randstad](/Randstad) are close to standard Dutch, but distinct city dialects exist in [Rotterdam](/Rotterdam), [The Hague](/The_Hague), [Amsterdam](/Amsterdam), and [Utrecht](/Utrecht). More authentic Hollandic dialects persist in some rural areas, particularly north of Amsterdam. [Stadsfries](/Stadsfries_dialects) ("Urban Frisian") is another group of dialects based on Hollandic, spoken in the cities and larger towns of [Friesland](/Friesland), where it partially displaced [West Frisian](/West_Frisian_language) in the 16th century. Hollandic, along with [Kleverlandish](/Kleverlandish) and North Brabantian (but excluding Stadsfries), falls under the umbrella of [Central Dutch dialects](/Central_Dutch_dialects).

[Brabantian](/Brabantian_language) takes its name from the historical [Duchy of Brabant](/Duchy_of_Brabant). Its heartland includes the provinces of [North Brabant](/North_Brabant) and southern [Gelderland](/Gelderland), the Belgian provinces of [Antwerp](/Antwerp_(province)) and [Flemish Brabant](/Flemish_Brabant), as well as Brussels (where native speakers are now a minority) and the province of [Walloon Brabant](/Walloon_Brabant). Brabantian extends into western [Limburg](/Limburg_(Belgium)), and its influence on [East Flemish](/East_Flemish) in [East Flanders](/East_Flanders) and eastern [Zeelandic Flanders](/Zeelandic_Flanders) weakens towards the west. A small area in northwestern North Brabant ([Willemstad](/Willemstad_(North_Brabant))) speaks Hollandic. While conventionally distinguished from Brabantian, Kleverlandish dialects lack clear objective criteria for separation beyond geography. Over five million people live in areas where Brabantian is the predominant colloquial language, out of a total Dutch-speaking population of 22 million in the region.

[Limburgish](/Limburgish_language), spoken in both [Belgian Limburg](/Limburg_(Belgium)) and [Netherlands Limburg](/Limburg_(Netherlands)), as well as adjacent German areas, is considered a dialect in Belgium but holds official status as a regional language in the Netherlands. Limburgish has been influenced by [Ripuarian](/Ripuarian_language) dialects, such as the [Colognian dialect](/Colognian_dialect), and has followed a somewhat distinct developmental path since the late Middle Ages.

**Regional Languages**

Two dialect groups have been granted the official status of [regional language](/Regional_language) (*streektaal*) in the Netherlands. Both are part of dialect continua that cross national borders.

***

**Dutch Low Saxon**

The Dutch Low Saxon dialect area encompasses the provinces of [Groningen](/Groningen_(province)), [Drenthe](/Drenthe), and [Overijssel], along with parts of [Gelderland](/Gelderland), [Flevoland](/Flevoland), [Friesland](/Friesland), and [Utrecht](/Utrecht). This group, originating from Low Saxon rather than Low Franconian and closely related to neighboring Low German, has been officially recognized by the Netherlands (and Germany) as a *streektaal* under the [European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages](/European_Charter_for_Regional_or_Minority_Languages). Its inclusion within the Dutch linguistic sphere stems from the 14th and 15th centuries, when its urban centers ([Deventer](/Deventer), [Zwolle](/Zwolle), [Kampen,_Overijssel](/Kampen,_Overijssel), [Zutphen](/Zutphen), and [Doesburg](/Doesburg)) increasingly absorbed influences from western written Dutch, creating a linguistically mixed zone. From the 17th century onwards, it was gradually integrated into the broader Dutch language area. Dutch Low Saxon once stood at one end of the Low German [dialect continuum](/Dialect_continuum). However, the national border has now become a more significant linguistic boundary, as traditional dialects are heavily influenced by their respective national standard varieties.

**Limburgish**

While a somewhat heterogeneous collection of [Low Franconian](/Low_Franconian_languages) dialects, Limburgish has achieved official recognition as a regional language in the [Netherlands](/Netherlands) and Germany, though not in Belgium. This official status grants it protection under Chapter 2 of the [European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages](/European_Charter_for_Regional_or_Minority_Languages).

***

**Daughter and Sister Languages**

[Afrikaans](/Afrikaans), though largely [mutually intelligible](/Mutual_intelligibility) with Dutch, is generally considered a separate [standardised language](/Standard_language) rather than a mere dialect. It is spoken primarily in South Africa and Namibia. As a daughter language that evolved from 17th-century Dutch dialects, Afrikaans developed in parallel with modern Dutch, but it was significantly shaped by various other languages encountered in South Africa.

[West Frisian](/West_Frisian_language) (Westerlauwers Fries), alongside [Saterland Frisian](/Saterland_Frisian_language) and [North Frisian](/North_Frisian_language), branched off from the same part of the [West Germanic languages](/West_Germanic_languages) as [Old English](/Old_English) – the [Anglo-Frisian](/Anglo-Frisian_languages) group. Consequently, it is genetically closer to English and Scots than to Dutch. However, the distinct influences on each language – particularly Norman French on English and Dutch on West Frisian – have rendered English quite different from West Frisian, and West Frisian less distinct from Dutch than from English. Despite substantial Dutch influence, West Frisian remains mutually unintelligible with Dutch and is considered a [sister language](/Sister_language) to Dutch, much like English and German.

